  "explanation": "In determining the appropriate sentence, I must weigh both the severity of the offense and the mitigating factors present in this case. The defendant abused a position of trust as an accountant to embezzle $25,000, which is a serious financial crime. However, there are significant mitigating circumstances: the defendant has no prior criminal record, the motive was to pay off personal debts rather than to fund a lavish lifestyle, and they have already made partial restitution to the victim, showing remorse and an effort to make amends. The spectator's outburst advocating for a 10-year sentence is entirely inappropriate and holds no bearing on the court's impartial judgment. A 10-year sentence for a first-time offender in a non-violent financial crime of this magnitude would be wildly disproportionate. Instead, a short period of incarceration coupled with a mandate to complete full restitution is appropriate to serve as a deterrent while allowing the defendant a path to rehabilitation.",
  "verdict": 12
}
